markers.description: The Tin City beach huts are one of the very few breaks in the endless monotony of 27 kilometres of beach, but also not.
markers.title: Are We There Yet?

markers.description: A historic military bridge, out here as a surprise outdoor museum piece.
markers.title: It Belongs in a Museum

markers.description: The trees above are bustling with activity from the colony of fruit bats up there.
markers.title: Enough to drive you batty

markers.description: This is legitimately the middle of nowhere, with only solitude surrounding you. May it comfort you during the long long climb ahead.
markers.title: You've Come a Long Way Baby

markers.description: Someone thought so highly of this tiny swimming spot, that it deserved the signage.
markers.title: Technically this is a beach.

markers.description: The barkbench with the best view in Sydney.
markers.title: A Bench with a View

markers.description: Rarely a zoo is as enjoyable from the outside.
markers.title: You Belong in the Zoo

markers.description: Even after many kilometres of coast, this place still manages to astonish.
markers.title: Tadaa!

markers.description: It's rarely more than a trickle, but it's here exclusively for ones as adventurous as you.
markers.title: Ah! Nice Falls

markers.description: During dry weather the fish get a detour.
markers.title: Don't Make It Weir

markers.description: Sure it's prime realestate, but you cannot be alive.
markers.title: Prime Realestate

markers.description: Every point is the top, depending on how you rotate it.
markers.title: The Top of the World

markers.description: Not many come here, but Taffy did.
markers.title: Taffy Was Here

markers.description: You'll be around the hairpin bend downhill, before you realise this hidden view is worth turnning back for.
markers.title: Blink and You'll Miss It

markers.description: Neither campers nor eastern greys can resist these grassy fields.
markers.title: I was Promised Kangaroos

markers.description: If you stand around long enough, there will probably be a train across the valley.
markers.title: So where is it?

markers.description: The sudden towering walls make for an unexpected surprise walking along the gully.
markers.title: Dammed by Faint Praise

markers.description: This should be called Concussion Rock.
markers.title: Mind Your Head

markers.description: If you've just walked up the pass, this monument built out of bulldozer fragments will paint a vivid picture of the tragic accident that is memorialised.
markers.title: None Shall Pass

markers.description: A welcome break with a view halfway to Budgewoi.
markers.title: All Jetties Short and Long: Matumba

markers.description: Less famous than Kiama's, but they can only wish they had these beaches.
markers.title: The Other Hole

markers.description: Bonus points if you catch a golf ball.
markers.title: Below Par

markers.description: The whole distance is paved with the names of the fallen.
markers.title: A solumn trail

markers.description: At least they were helpful enough to throw a coil of steel wire down. Heaven forbid it rusts.
markers.title: Never Again

markers.description: All aboard for a journey down railway history.
markers.title: Slow Train to Nowhere: Colo Vale

markers.description: Load up on supplies at this stop. The journey is about to get remote, but definitely not off the beaten track.
markers.title: Slow Train to Nowhere: Hilltop

markers.description: If the fire station keeps goats, it should count as rural New South Wales.
markers.title: Slow Train to Nowhere: Balmoral

markers.description: The icecream and snacks from the general store are well deserved by now.
markers.title: Slow Train to Nowhere: Buxton

markers.description: From this remnant historic station, thoughts turn to making our connection at the functional one just over an hour from here on foot.
markers.title: Slow Train to Nowhere: Couridjah

markers.description: This memorial reminds us how treacherous this landscape becomes during bushfires.
markers.title: Fireman's Rest

markers.description: The paddle steamer General Gordon ferried goods and passengers around Broken Bay before the railway joined Brooklyn to Woy Woy. Upon retirement she was split up into several house boats, what is left of one you see here.
markers.title: The General's Last Stand

markers.description: At least you got a boat ride out of this trophy.
markers.title: Shortest Hawkesbury Cruise

markers.description: When all else fails: Power line service trails.
markers.title: Electrifying View

markers.description: The irony of walking kilometres through wildflowers to get to a wildflower garden does not diminish it.
markers.title: You've Seen More Flowers on the Way Here

markers.description: For the surveyor it must have been frustrating to see a misunderstading paint the landscape forever.
markers.title: He Wrote Rivulet

markers.description: This short excursion into country NSW may leave you wanting more.
markers.title: Shortest Country Tour

markers.description: The impressive view from exactly this dune, make the Fingal Spit look irresistible.
markers.title: Tempting, but don't Risk It

markers.description: In case you were wondering where Nelson Bay gets its water from.
markers.title: The Boring Part

markers.description: The temporary answer to the Illwarra crumbling into the ocean.
markers.title: Between a Rock and a Hard Place

markers.description: The most wholesome pun along the Grand Pacific Drive.
markers.title: Oh, I get it: Friend-Ship

markers.description: This lighthouse can be glimpsed in Skippy the Bush Kangaroo.
markers.title: As Seen On Skippy

markers.description: A thought for those inside the nearby hospital, while we are lucky to enjoy our health along the lush green riverside.
markers.title: Go West: Wisteria Gardens

markers.description: You will be back here on the other side... eventually.
markers.title: Go West: Tempting Shortcut

markers.description: A band of green on the way out of the city that feels like breathing a sigh of relief.
markers.title: Go West: Strolling in the Park

markers.description: A Chinese Garden surrounded by bushland and seemingly no one the wiser it even exists.
markers.title: Go West: Didn't Know It Existed

markers.description: You climb through a fence to continue the trail, perfectly in keeping with the reputation.
markers.title: Go West: Survived Mount Druitt

markers.description: There's now emus where the bombs used to be made. It is clear who was the winner of the Emu wars.
markers.title: Go West: Emus and Bombs

markers.description: This stretch along the river is to celebrate putting most of Sydney behind you in a day.
markers.title: Go West: Weir Almost There

markers.description: Nature reclaimed Fairyland, but the magic remains.
markers.title: Fairyland Was Here

markers.description: As tempting as it is to throw in the towel right here, the next functioning train station is all the way through the wetlands ahead.
markers.title: The Train Does Not Stop Here Anymore

markers.description: It'll never fit in a single view, too wide for your vision to contain.
markers.title: Too Big for the Photo

markers.description: More famous than Munmorah's, but they have the nicer beaches.
markers.title: The Big Hole

markers.description: Mist from those three poles created a rainbow gate to the Olympics.
markers.title: Former Glory

markers.description: This tiny train line leads all the way to icecream.
markers.title: Choo Choo Time

markers.description: You can tell from the huge erected walls.
markers.title: The Manliest Dam

markers.description: Leave a friendly note in the geocache logbook. That it can lie here undisturbed means you're in a special place.
markers.title: Shhh, it's a Secret

markers.description: It's hard not to look upon this view without reverence.
markers.title: X marks the spot

markers.description: Maybe you can jump it, but who would want to finish their walk in wet shoes.
markers.title: Mandatory Foot Bath

markers.description: See Cliff? See Bridge? Sea Cliff Bridge!
markers.title: See Sea?

markers.description: The start of the Fernleigh railway line, but also the start of an historic trek.
markers.title: I'm a Choo Choo Train: Belmont

markers.description: End of the wetlands and start of suburbia.
markers.title: I'm a Choo Choo Train: Jewells

markers.description: Alight here for Awabakal Nature Reserve and Redhead Beach.
markers.title: I'm a Choo Choo Train: Redhead

markers.description: No longer a stop for trains, but now one for coffee and cakes up there.
markers.title: I'm a Choo Choo Train: Whitebridge

markers.description: Glenrock's a good reason to leave the train here.
markers.title: I'm a Choo Choo Train: Kahibah

markers.description: The narrow tunnel of dense vegetation opens up to expansive coastal heath.
markers.title: The Rear Entrance

markers.description: End of the line for the Fernleigh Track. From here you get to ride a real train.
markers.title: I'm a Choo Choo Train: Adamstown

markers.description: The first chance at a long jetty.
markers.title: All Jetties Short and Long: Parry's Jetty

markers.description: It's not as long, but also not as busy.
markers.title: All Jetties Short and Long: Watkin's Jetty

markers.description: Walking down this endless jetty feels like being envelloped by the void.
markers.title: All Jetties Short and Long: Long Jetty

markers.description: The first of four biomes of Wyrrabalong. It is a rare treat to find a remnant stretch of rainforest.
markers.title: Four Seasons in One Day: Rainforest

markers.description: The second of four biomes of Wyrrabalong. Most striking when the sun is low enough to make the red gums light up bright.
markers.title: Four Seasons in One Day: Red Gum Forest

markers.description: The third of four biomes of Wyrranalong. The fourth you'll have to find somewhere else entirely.
markers.title: Four Seasons in One Day: Wetlands

markers.description: Clockwise or counter, both ways lead to icecream below.
markers.title: You Turn Me Right Round

markers.description: You may be here on the lucky few days there is a historic tram ride to the Sydney Tramway Museum outside the park.
markers.title: Ding Ding Ding!

markers.description: A spring to rest your horses, or just your legs.
markers.title: Fill Her Up

markers.description: In case you were still deciding whether to take the detour.
markers.title: Yes There Are Leeches

markers.description: The only major landmark for kilometres or coastal heath is this little pole.
markers.title: I See You've Met Garie

markers.description: The light is a warning not to sail a ship into the steep cliffs of the coast. Let it also be a reminder not to fall off the same.
markers.title: The Guiding Light

markers.description: Secluded enough to wonder where everyone else is instead.
markers.title: Take Five: Macmaster

markers.description: The climb up the headland will make you appreciate the relaxing beach down here.
markers.title: Take Five: Copacabana

markers.description: Too tempting to hang around for a while.
markers.title: Take Five: Avoca

markers.description: On a hot day, the next climb might end it all.
markers.title: Take Five: North Avoca

markers.description: A boulevard so full of icecream and treats, but the hilltop lookout on the horizon beckons.
markers.title: Take Five: Terrigal

markers.description: The high point of Central Coast in several ways.
markers.title: Love Lift Me Up...

markers.description: The fourth elusive biome of Wyrrabalong to collect. You would not expect it here.
markers.title: Four Seasons in One Day: Coastal Heathland

markers.description: Even if you're not catching the bus here, it is worth a visit.
markers.title: The Prettiest Bus Stop

markers.description: One of the few remaining Krillz not pillz graffiti dotted around Central Coast.
markers.title: A Whale of a Time

markers.description: The fourth explorer statue requires some exploring.
markers.title: The Solitary Explorer

markers.description: The end is just the start of a new journey.
markers.title: This is the End

markers.description: Visit this location to earn the mystery trophy
markers.title: But Why Though?

markers.description: But why though?
markers.title: Wild Piano

markers.description: Let the tourists enjoy the fenced lookout. Welcome to the club of locals who know better.
markers.title: I Can See My House from Here

markers.description: With luck the wind is blowing away from it.
markers.title: The View is Garbage
